Research Objective¶

The research objective of this project is to first identify the key features and the degree to which they contribute to an AIRBNB's listing price using historical listings data, and then create a empirical pricing prediction model to predict a nightly listing price for a listing in the Austin, TX. metropolitan area.

Data Description¶

Data Sources¶

AIRBNB Dataset¶

The airbnb dataset is divided into three subsets listings, calendar, and reviews for each geographic area they support. Each subset is available in a monthly timeframe from the AIRBNB website. I downloaded a year's worth of data and extracted, renamed, and reorganized the CSV file into manageable directories.

  • Source: AIRBNB
  • Source URL: http://insideairbnb.com/get-the-data.html
  • City: Austin, Tx
  • Data Range: August 2018 - July 2019
  • License: Creative Commons CC0 1.0
  • Subsets used listings

Austin Crime Map¶

The Austin Crime Map is a CSV record of incidents that the Austin Police Department reported and responded to. It contains information about each incident and and the highest level of offense that occurred.

  • Source: Austin City Government Open Data Portal
  • Source URL: https://data.austintexas.gov/Public-Safety/Crime-Reports-2018-Map/fc3e-daxz
  • City: Austin, Tx
  • Data Range: 01/01/2018 and 12/31/2018
  • License: Public Domain

Data Exploration¶

Data Preparation¶

Before being able to explore the data some cleaning and feature engineering was necessary.

Drop Duplicates¶

Since the listings dataset contains listings from several months aggregated together there are bound to be duplicates. The duplicates were dropped based on the subset of the columns listing_id, price, and month.

A soft drop dropped duplicates with listing_id, price, and month matching.

A hard drop dropped duplicates with listing_id, and price

Align Datasets by Zipcode¶

To use the datasets together they were aligned on the common feature zipcode. An intersection was made of the zipcode columns from each set and records with zipcodes outside the intersection were dropped. This operation results in no loss of data for our main Listings DataFrame.

Crime Rate¶

Crime Rate of an area may be a possible feature when determining a listing rent price. To calculate a crime rate per zipcode crime_count was divided by the number of listings in that zipcode. This value was used to create crime_rate by regions as well.

Price Analysis¶

Since the model will be trying to predict price an investigation into the price distributions is necessary. The statistics show a very high standard deviation and far left field outliers. 95% of all prices are below $1000.00 dollars, but the max is 25 times that.

Price Boxplot¶

Price Distribution¶

The distribution is not normal. It is skewed to the right and has several peaks beyond the mean. This could be attributed to AIRBNB renters wanting to price rent at intervals of 50 or 100 dollars.

Remove Outliers¶

To remove outliers I used the log(1+x) function. The log values below 3.5 and above 6.5 were removed as outliers. The upper limit was close to the 1.5 x IQR + Q75 value which was $562.00.

Reviews Analysis¶

In this section reviews are analyzed. Each review is a an integer value. The rating score is the overall score for a listing and is between 0 and 100. The remaining 6 scores, accuracy, cleanliness, check-in, communication, location, and value are set between 1 and 10. There does not seem to be a very strong relationship between reviews and price. As long as the reviews are not terribly negative the listing is not impact by the review factor.

Summary¶

In this project I tried to create a nightly AIRBNB listing price prediction model based on the geographic, physical, and monetary aspects of a listing. Out of the models I tried Extreme Gradient Boosted trees performed the best. The RSME value of the trained model was very high at around 88. Since RSME is in the same units as the prediction a +- $88.00 deviation from the predicted price makes the model not very useful for predicting purposes. The r2 value was around 0.57 so 43 percent of variations are unexplained. These I believe are due to the feature set not capturing all aspects of the listing such as photos and host statuses. My research goal of identifying key listing features that contribute to price was somewhat successful, as the model identified accommodates, bedrooms, bathrooms, and zipcode as useful features. Furthermore the dataset was relatively small with an abnormal distribution leading to difficulties in model prediction. However I do think that the same process if applied to a bigger AIRBNB city such as New York or Paris can result in a better predictive model.
